node.text:
Its been one year since i posted my first microvideo here. So much changed in my life. i spend hours taking samples, going through them, observing and waiting for the most interesting moments, editing Videos, reading through literature, talking to you guys. I kind of found a meaning in life as well as the beauty in nature which is everywhere but invisible. 
To be honest im a person who looses easily interest in new hobbies. I often start something new but give it up because it seems meaningless. 
But this time it is different. I have the feeling I can interest you for something you maybe never thought about. And I hope im able to teach you some stuff about microorganisms or make you happy with funny moments i watch under my scope.

I often get messages in which you are thanking me for my content. But actually I have to thank all of YOU for supporting me and keep me going on. 
Without YOU I would have long ago stopped searching for new samples and spending time in front of my microscope. 💙

You are all awesome and I hope you will support me in the future too 🦠
.
.

Did you know that Ciliates can form resting cysts too?  Other organisms like Rotifera and Tardigrades do the same as well! -------------‐

love you all 💙

waterfleas
-small crustaceans
-most are 0.2 -6.00mm long
-reproduce sexually and asexually
-eggs can be transported over land by wind and hatch when they reach favourable conditions
-most live in freshwater
-eat plants and fungi
-important food source for fish

•sessile organisms
•all organisms they are able to catch

•their guts contain enzyme which break down the devoured food

•Macrostomum means 'big-mouthed'
•their long mouth is connected to the gut by a muscular pharynx which can expand to almost the width of the animal

•lay single eggs
•can endure high starvation
•have adhesive glands on the end of their tail

Did you all eat enough? 

-𝒆𝒙𝒑𝒍𝒂𝒏𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏, 𝒊𝒏𝒇𝒐𝒔 𝒂𝒃𝒐𝒖𝒕 𝒐𝒓𝒈𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒔𝒎 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒔𝒆𝒕𝒖𝒑 𝒃𝒆𝒍𝒐𝒘- 

Hope you all are eating enough and never throw anything away! Like Sir Eatnfart. This species of worm have a biiig mouth and swallow complete waterfleas. Sir Eatnfart did so too but got stuck between coverglass and slide.... what can I say- the result is seeable in the video.
BUT before you get sad now and blame me! No worries. BOTH parts of this worm go on living. One part will grow back a tail, the other one will grow back a head and tadaa- Sir Eatnfart has a brother Sir Eatnpoop. 

If anyone knows something about the species of the worm let me know- until now i failed to find some informations.
----- 

I got a message two days ago which confused me a lot. Someone blamed me for stealing their video idea pointing on my video of myself where I wrote I spent a lot time writing descriptions and get 'whats that?' comments.
I surely never saw a video like that from the person who is mad at me so I have NO clue what i copied. Sadly I didnt even got an explanation but got blocked after asking WHAT exactly I did wrong.
It kinda makes me sad AND mad because im not going around and stealing video ideas- its stuff that randomly pops up in my head. And if someone has the feeling I stole something from them- Im someone who can be talked to.
Blaming me for something and blocking me afterwards is kind of uncool and surely nothing grown up people should do.
I know I did nothing on purpose 🥲 

Im not going to mention the account of them! I dont want to start a hate or something here but only tell whats in my mind since two days.
Im easily triggered to overthink things and dream about that stuff which is kind of exhausting. 
Its just something in my head which had to be written down.

While watching this amoeba i recognized some beating cilia inside- this fellow caught a stentor, an unicellular organism. He should have been the dinner for the amoeba- but managed to get away. I love how it slowly squishes out of the amoeba and fastly swims away 😹
Imagine what crazy hunters amoeba would be if they could move faster. Swallowing and eating EVERYTHING in their way 🥲 

I recently thought about which microorganism is the most known. Amoeba and Tardigrade are well known- what was YOUR first microorganism you got to know about?

Tardigrades may be the most known microrganisms and yet I wonder why theres no Pokemon designed after it 🤔

------

------
𝙜𝙚𝙣𝙪𝙨
?
Phylum: Tardigrada
𝙡𝙞𝙫𝙚 𝙞𝙣
•freshwater, marine environments, moss
𝙖𝙥𝙥𝙚𝙖𝙧𝙖𝙣𝙘𝙚
•most are smaller than a millimeter
•barrel shaped bodies
•body has four segments (not counting the head), four pairs of legs and feet with four to eight claws each
𝙛𝙚𝙚𝙙𝙞𝙣𝙜
•plant cells, algae and also other organisms 
•the mouth is armed with stylets which are used to pierce their food 
𝙬𝙤𝙧𝙩𝙝 𝙩𝙤 𝙠𝙣𝙤𝙬
•known as water bears or moss piglet
•have a nerve system
•can only grow through moulting
•can reproduce sexually or parthenogenic
•are able to survive in extreme environments- temperatures, pressure, dehydration, radiaten
BUT they are not immortal! 
-many people believe tardigrades are immortal due to their ability to survive extreme conditions. They only survive those building a cyst and 'resting' until the conditions become better
•normal life span 3-4 months

Im sorry. I know this has nothing to do with microscopy but I had to share my feelings somewhere. 

Today the worst possible for a pet mom happened- one of my cats suddenly passed away.
Im heartbroken and still cant believe it. Dont feel like beeing able to make any posts in the following time.

I hope youll understand that and forgive me. 

Zelda was just three years old and she didnt had any health issues.
Yesterday night she slept beside my pillow me holding her paw like most nights. This morning we had some cuddles and played around.
It was nothing wrong with her. Didnt had any different behaviour in the last weeks/days.
But suddenly this morning she started breathing heavily.
She was brought to an emergency clinic but passed away while beeing treated.
The vet couldnt tell what caused this dead. 

Its unbelievable how much we take life for granted. Thats something I had to realize today. 
I never will get cuddles with her again, never will have her paws and butt in my face- one of her favourite spots, never will meow meow to each other again.
No more stomach massages for me, no more getting mad because she scratches my bed and chair although she had a big cat tree.
She will never again rub her face all over my scope making everything full of cat hair and drive me crazy. 
She will never look at me again- with her judging eyes. Never tickle me again with her whiskers while Im asleep.
Never see her derp face again. Never again running through the apartment calling her each time a different nickname. Never getting the oppurtunity again telling her what a little witch she is. A mini little monster.

Life feels so unfair and cold right now. I cant even put it all in words.
Farewell- you will be missed my little princess. My Minimaus, my little minini 💔😔

Attack on Stentor season 1- airing this summer 

-𝒆𝒙𝒑𝒍𝒂𝒏𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏, 𝒊𝒏𝒇𝒐𝒔 𝒂𝒃𝒐𝒖𝒕 𝒐𝒓𝒈𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒔𝒎 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒔𝒆𝒕𝒖𝒑 𝒃𝒆𝒍𝒐𝒘- 

This summer chosen cinemas will show the new movie 'attack on Stentor'. It tells the story of the little Ereh trying to survive in a world full of blue giant whales. Be prepared for a lot of action, drama, tears, death and love. Will Mikasa and Ereh survive this world and be happy in the end? 

I dont have any new videos soo heres the announcement for the airing cinema movie of attack on stentor. 😇
The weather today is crazy here so no new sames today too.
Actually I have some videos I wanted to post but it takes a whilw to prepare the videos, write the description etc. Though lately im wondering: why do I even spent hours writing texts? 😹 some videos get so many comments asking 'whats that?' while I spent two decades to make a overseeable list. Its beyond my power to make it even more clear 🥺 
If you have any ideas or tipps- let me know! 

Love you all and wish you a great sunday 💙

Ok so to be honest I dont know why Charmy junior is so slow catching his food. Sometimes they are just a little dumb. You also can see the stentors defense by contracting into a ball. But that isnt useful against these flatworms at all.
